text: <@UUPTPUHCK>, I just joined the volunteer teams to help with <#CUS6NK0E5|analytics-live_charts> <@U010ERKTCAK> suggested that I connect with you. <@UUM7J4EJX> has provided helpful connection and access to data. I want to try some classification methods to see if I can uncover some insights in the smoothed country trend analysis to partition into different groups objectively. I am can analyze data offline. I have programming experience with Fortran, Matlab, IDL, Java and Python with less toward the end of the list, so will need others to code up the ideas that I develop regarding potential automation and classification if they seem promising. Thanks to everyone who is volunteering their time to work on this. It's been two days since I started with Slack, so have patience if I am not up on the intricacies of the interface.

attachments: [{'service_name': 'medRxiv', 'title': 'Humoral immune response and prolonged PCR positivity in a cohort of 1343 SARS-CoV 2 patients in the New York City region', 'title_link': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.30.20085613v1', 'text': 'Background: Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) has caused a global pandemic. The percentage of infected individuals who seroconvert is still an open question. In addition, it has been shown in some individuals that viral genome can still be detected at considerable time post symptom resolution. Here we investigated both seroconversion and PCR-positivity in a large cohort of convalescent serum donors in New York City. Methods: Individuals with confirmed or suspected SARS-CoV-2 infection were screened via PCR for presence of viral genome and via enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay for presence of anti SARS-CoV-2 spike antibodies. Results: All but three confirmed SARS-CoV-2 patients seroconverted to the SARS-CoV-2 spike while only 37.4% of suspected SARS-CoV-2 patients seroconverted. PCR-positivity was detected up to 28 days from symptom resolution. Conclusions: Here we show that the vast majority of confirmed COVID19 patients seroconvert, potentially providing immunity to reinfection. We also report that in a large proportion of individuals, viral genome can be detected via PCR in the upper respiratory tract for weeks post symptom resolution, but it is unclear if this signal represents infectious virus. ### Competing Interest Statement The authors have declared no competing interest. ### Funding Statement Work on SARS-CoV-2 immunity in the Krammer is supported by the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease (NIAID) Collaborative Influenza Vaccine Innovation Centers (CIVIC) contract 75N93019C00051 and the NIAID Centers of Excellence for Influenza Research and Surveillance (CEIRS) contract HHSN272201400008C as well as institutional and philanthropic funding. ### Author Declarations All relevant ethical guidelines have been followed; any necessary IRB and/or ethics committee approvals have been obtained and details of the IRB/oversight body are included in the manuscript. Yes All necessary patient/participant consent has been obtained and the appropriate institutional forms have been archived. Yes I understand that all clinical trials and any other prospective interventional studies must be registered with an ICMJE-approved registry, such as <http://ClinicalTrials.gov|ClinicalTrials.gov>. I confirm that any such study reported in the manuscript has been registered and the trial registration ID is provided (note: if posting a prospective study registered retrospectively, please provide a statement in the trial ID field explaining why the study was not registered in advance). Yes I have followed all appropriate research reporting guidelines and uploaded the relevant EQUATOR Network research reporting checklist(s) and other pertinent material as supplementary files, if applicable. Yes Authors are responsible for all data presented in the manuscript.', 'fallback': 'medRxiv: Humoral immune response and prolonged PCR positivity in a cohort of 1343 SARS-CoV 2 patients in the New York City region', 'ts': 1588662000, 'from_url': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.30.20085613v1', 'service_icon': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/sites/default/files/images/favicon.ico', 'id': 1, 'original_url': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.30.20085613v1'}]

text:
*<!channel>* :exclamation: *DAILY SCANNING UPDATE* :exclamation:
As a reminder, Tuesday/Wednesday/Thursday office/work hours are there to provide you all with space to discuss projects including getting more information on them if you're interested in jumping on board but are not quite sure how to.

Our current active projects:
9 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
• Pandemic Management Documentation (*Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol> let's help <@UV2HZ2CF9> and <@UV6E4SWTH> get info relevant to local communities in states to underscore how to #CrushTheCurve in the US*)
• Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)
• A list of the best Websites of lists related to Covid19 or ECV network (Due Date 4/20/2020)
• Combating PPE fraud (Open call for scanners to help the PPE fraud team fact check sources of info)
PHAGE projects. PHAGE is a platform for providing users i.e. the general public and patients with the info they need to be aware of COVID-19, their options for healthcare access/treatment, and more. Check out <http://phageco.com|phageco.com> for more info. Some scanners are already working on these but we need project leads to step forward! Don't be shy, we'll help each other find our footing. These are :rotating_light: *top priority projects* :rotating_light: 
• COVID-19 Palliative Care (Due Date: 5/17/2020)
• COVID-19 Mental Health (Due Date: 5/17/2020)
• COVID-19 Pulmonary Methodologies (Due Date: 5/17/2020)
• COVID-19 Tele-health/Tele-Medicine (Due Date: 5/17/2020)
• COVID-19 Long-Term Health Effects (Due Date: 5/17/2020)

2 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
• Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* :rotating_light:* *project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete and death numbers are complete. The dataset is only missing shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating the ACAPS sheet, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

• Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread> *Andrew could really use some help here since he's been focusing on the shutdown/borders dataset*.


1 Projects(s) with Research complete
• Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Due Date 4/30/2020)

*<!channel>* Here's a schedule of our weekly :calendar: recurring scanning Zoom sessions. This message will be pinned to the channel for future reference. Zoom details follow in the thread. I've now changed things so that every meeting uses the same Zoom link for ease of access :slightly_smiling_face: Please be aware though that since I'm using my personal meeting room you can't join before I do. If the link isn't working wait a minute or two and try again.

Please come to these when you have time, I really want us to get to know each other, hear from you on how the team is doing, take in suggestions for how I can do better as a lead or how the team can improve overall, and provide you with ample opportunities to collaboratively work on and discuss projects.

*General scanning team general meeting and social hour (Hang out and discuss the current/next week's activities):*
Saturdays at 11am EST
Sundays at 5pm EST

*Open scanning office/working hours (talk about day-to-day issues, get info on and check in to discuss projects, work on projects with other scanners live for company, or just say hello):*
Tuesdays at 10am-12pm EST
Wednesdays at 12-2pm EST
Thursdays at 2-4pm EST

text:
:rotating_light: Attention <!channel> :rotating_light:  we had a big batch of scanning requests come in yesterday with more on the way, this is all part of a big effort to create a curated feed of information for potential and actual COVID-19 patients on various fronts (awareness, education, access, treatment, caregiving, etc.). Check out <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> for info on each project. We need all hands on deck with these projects. All this information will ultimately end up available to the public on the <https://phageco.com/|PHAGE platform> but will also be incredibly valuable to other ECV teams.

Please come by office/group work hours today (12-2pm EST) or tomorrow (2-4pm EST), or reach out to me so we can chat and I can walk you through <https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdpg41fA4cXNPyYHh2kMl6sThyBK1JHl_WJ8aE25Sbd87k9Gw/viewform?usp=sf_link|the form> that we're using to curate the information sources we find for each project. <@U011XBASR1C> (who has put in these requests) will also be present during our general meeting this Saturday to answer questions. Let's do this!

text:
*<!channel>* :exclamation: *DAILY SCANNING UPDATE* :exclamation:
We're about to have a big influx of scanning projects geared towards providing COVID-19 patients or potential patients with resources to better understand their condition and options at any given stage (being un-infected, infected but mild symptoms, severe symptoms, recovering). All this info will be available to the public via a platform developed by <@U011XBASR1C>. We'll be using a scoring system to rate the information we scan for legibility and usefulness which I'll walk team members through. Please come to office hours for demonstrations or contact me if interested. I"ll start putting out the project requests later today.

Our current active projects:
4 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (*Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol> let's help <@UV2HZ2CF9> make the push to #CrushTheCurve in the US*)
Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)
A list of the best Websites of lists related to Covid19 or ECV network (Due Date 4/20/2020)
Combating PPE fraud (Due Date: 5/5/2020)


3 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. *This project is currently on hold pending conversations happening with external collaborators.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area.

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* :rotating_light:* *project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete and death numbers are complete. The dataset is only missing shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating the ACAPS sheet, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread> *Andrew could really use some help here since he's been focusing on the shutdown/borders dataset*.


1 Projects(s) with Research complete
Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Main responsibility at this point is putting the information already gathered into a useful format in collaboration with the requester <@UUQ3KD4P4>

text:
*<!channel>* :exclamation: *DAILY SCANNING UPDATE* :exclamation:
Tomorrow I'll be hosting open scanning team office hours on Zoom between 12-2pm EST :alarm_clock:.  *I especially encourage those actively working on scanning projects and new team members to attend*. Come by to update everyone on how your projects are going, discuss any roadblocks you've encountered, get your questions answered on how to get involved, and also just hang out for a bit.There may or may not be a low key 30-minute yoga session involved too somewhere in there too...

Our current active projects:
4 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (*Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol> let's help <@UV2HZ2CF9> make the push to #CrushTheCurve in the US*)
Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)
A list of the best Websites of lists related to Covid19 or ECV network (Due Date 4/20/2020)
Combating PPE fraud (Due Date: 5/5/2020)

1 orphaned project in need of a lead since <@U010K8GMXSS> is now working on <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> projects
Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>. Main responsibility at this point is putting the information already gathered into a useful format in collaboration with the requester <@UUQ3KD4P4>

3 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. This is a *top priority project* :rotating_light:*.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area. *Contact Sarah to jump on board!*

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* :rotating_light: project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete, now we need to fill in shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? text:
*<!channel>* DAILY PROJECTS UPDATE

Our current active projects:
4 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol>)
Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)
A list of the best Websites of lists related to Covid19 or ECV network (Due Date 4/20/2020)
Combating PPE fraud (Due Date: 5/5/2020)

1 orphaned project in need of a lead since <@U010K8GMXSS> is now working on <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> projects
Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>. Main responsibility at this point is putting the information already gathered into a useful format in collaboration with the requester <@UUQ3KD4P4>

3 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. This is a *top priority project.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area. *Contact Sarah to jump on board!*

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete, now we need to fill in shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread>

[{'fallback': "[April 27th, 2020 5:51 PM] lazarus.benjamin: Major thanks to <@U2ED1L71D> <@U010LMFBCQJ> <@UUE3EV5J5><@UURUK8NHJ> <@U3P244XED> for helping pull off today's press blitz around the COVID-19 letter to Gov Northam!

Next Steps:
-- Try to pitch to bigger national outlets (anyone able to help with that... AP/WaPo/NYT/Reuters)
-- Seek buy in from labor unions, NAACP to support recs. 120+ scientist/academics/physicians signed but they don't have political clout
-- Give governor a couple days to respond to letter
-- If we don't hear back, we'll try reaching out through various channels

Here are the stories that ran today:

text:
*<!channel>* DAILY PROJECTS UPDATE

Our current active projects:
4 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol>)
Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)
A list of the best Websites of lists related to Covid19 or ECV network (Due Date 4/20/2020)
Track down white house testing site list (4/27/2020)


4 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. This is a *top priority project.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area. *Contact Sarah to jump on board!*

Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Team Lead <@U010K8GMXSS>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete, now we need to fill in shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread>

<!channel> CALL TO ACTION: we need more active scanners to join the scanning effort.  HELP US RECRUIT today and ongoing as part of this teams culture!
• go to  <#CUVB0V2KV|general-onboarding-intro_yourself> scroll back through and write replies to people who seem like they would like scanning based on intros -- “Hi @new person  and welcome you may enjoy the work we are doing in <#C010KQ9TC1W|analytics-scanning> where take requests to find information from other channels and projects in here! introduce yourself on the channel or check out the pinned post there if this is of interest to you. we have a fun collaborative team of people working together that you can plug right in with! reach out with any questions” 
• It often helps to Direct Message  and make a SOCIAL connection “what are you interested in?” and even try connecting by phone (like our Team Lead does!)
• even if someone doesn’t jump right in they may join the channel get more comfortable and do so in the future. 
• the more scanners, the more scanning Requests can be fulfilled! Greeting is Fun!
GO TEAM SCAN! :first_place_medal:

text:
*<!channel>* MORNING PROJECTS UPDATE

The scanning team has been asked if we can take over putting together the ECV daily updates (<https://www.endcoronavirus.org/daily-update>). I will work to pull together talent from other channels to hopefully have a dedicated channel/team for this, but it would be useful to have one or two scanners on said team. A*ny team members with python/tableau experience and any who would be interested in helping look up/input data on a regular basis for the updates please contact me asap.*

Our current active projects:
2 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Look for more detail and sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> or contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (Open call for scanners to help with <#C011W8H192A|outreach-usa> and <#C012TES47Q8|outreach-usa-protocol>)
Campaign Reviews (Due Date 4/25/2020)


4 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. This is a *top priority project.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area. *Contact Sarah to jump on board!*

Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Team Lead <@U010K8GMXSS>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. This is a *top priority* project to help develop a graph that will be used for messaging. Dates of local transmission are complete, now we need to fill in shutdown/border closure dates which can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread>

1 Project(s) with Research Complete. Here are their descriptions:
Effect of implementing/lifting key measures over time (Due Date OVERDUE)
*Please report your findings!*

text:
*<!channel>* DAILY PROJECTS UPDATE

The scanning team has been asked to take over putting together the ECV daily updates (<https://www.endcoronavirus.org/daily-update>) *any team members with python/tableau experience please contact me asap*. Our current active projects:

1 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> and contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (Due Date 4/22/2020)


1 Project(s) with Assigned Team Lead. *_These projects need mini-team members_. _Contact the mini-team lead or post on the relevant thread in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> to jump onboard one of these projects._* Here are their descriptions:
Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread>


3 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. This is a *top priority project.* Primary use will be from the covid-19 scientific database team to help staff these locations and provide additional scientific support. Multiple secondary uses for other projects who also need these details for data tracking, or communicating with the local area. *Contact Sarah to jump on board!*

Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Team Lead <@U010K8GMXSS>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date 4/20/2020)
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. I've been using <https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports|WHO situation reports> to find dates of first local transmission for the most part, shutdown/border closure dates can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

Long term effects of Covid -19 infection (No specific lead but lots of work done by <@U01110U5YRL>, Due Date 4/26/2020)
How you can help: Add to the links being posted on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C0100TMK58V/p1587221304052700|this thread>


1 Project(s) with Research Complete. Here are their descriptions:
Effect of implementing/lifting key measures over time (Due Date 4/21/2020)
*Please report your findings!*

text: URGENT! I was looking into the actual number and type of tests available.  Found most were antibody based, and collected in the sinus with a swab.  This alone is awful diagnostics.  COVID is a lower respiratory illness, and would only show up via lovage (not nose).  And through something like qPCR. Also made in China - quality product?

text:
Hey <!channel>, a few updates from Sunday's scanning team meeting:
1. <#C0108BH13PD|analytics-scanning-projects> activity will now be merged into <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>, please use threads under project requests to help organize mini-teams, post findings, share Google docs (if they're being used) for aggregating findings, etc. to reiterate, *we are no longer using <#C0108BH13PD|analytics-scanning-projects>* 
2. We'll now be posting daily project updates in this chanel including information on how you can jump in on them to help, they will be pinned to the channel every time they come out. 
3. Weekly meetings will be happening regularly on Saturdays at 8am PST and Sundays at 2pm PST
4. Be sure to check out the *<https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wrf4zYH7TA4ChhIefyDQ8wIVKAEJxu-o6jIz_XJwQFE/edit|Scanning Welcome Doc>* as it is frequently evolving along with the team
5. If you're interested in helping to actively recruit new team members please contact me or <@U010ERKTCAK> or <@U010K8GMXSS>, help us build the team up!
6. As always, feel free to teach out to me if you need help jumping on a project

<!channel> EVENING PROJECTS UPDATE

1 Project(s) Requested. _*These projects need leads/teams to get them off the ground! Sign up under the relevant post in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> and contact <@UUPTPUHCK> to get started.*_ Here are their descriptions:
Pandemic Management Documentation (Due Date 4/22/2020)

1 Project(s) with Assigned Team Lead. _*Contact the relevant mini-team lead or post on the relevant thread in <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal> to jump onboard one of these projects.*_ Here are their descriptions:

Zoning guidance for Zone-owners (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, OVERDUE)
How you can help: Look up articles on countries that only have shutdowns of select regions/cities and how they manage travel in and out of quarantined areas e.g. is it allowed? Sanitation measures used? <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587146988019400|Post in this thread>

US COVID-19 testing locations by States and Counties (Team Lead <@U011XAHHD7G>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Work on filling in <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1R4CDPiDMIKHcgZzlHcEcXKdtoHmS4p2uIIpf_eKrzoI/edit#gid=0|this sheet> or share potentially useful information (e.g. testing sites databases) on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587130549018700|this thread>. Contact Sarah to jump on board!

2 Project(s) with Assigned Team Members. *_They might need more help, ask the mini-team lead or check out the relevant thread on <#C011PFC8J21|analytics-scanning-portal>_.* Here are their descriptions:
Mapping the Virus and InfoTech Divide (Team Lead <@U010K8GMXSS>, Due Date 4/30/2020)
How you can help: Find publicly available datasets that track internet usage at the smallest geographic unit possible (counties, provinces/states, etc.) and share links to them on <https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1587071857018600|this thread>

Shutdown/Border Closing and Deaths (Team Lead <@UUPTPUHCK>, Due Date 4/20/2020)
How you can help: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1j6VhMtYny3gjwJa37hxbgiZuRvN1b2wN8f9kFlIUGqY/edit#gid=0|Fill in in this sheet>. I've been using <https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports|WHO situation reports> to find dates of first local transmission for the most part, shutdown/border closure dates can be obtained from the <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset|ACAPS dataset>, and death numbers can be acquired from Johns Hopkins data. Contact Andrew if you need help navigating these datasets, otherwise it's a simple plug-and-chug operation.

1 Project(s) with Research Complete. Here are their descriptions:
Effect of implementing/lifting key measures over time (Due Date 4/21/2020)
*Please report your findings!*

'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Date:\xa0', 'style': {'bold': True}}, {'type': 'text', 'text': 'April 17, 2020 at 6:43:37 PM EDT
'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': 'To:\xa0', 'style': {'bold': True}}, {'type': 'link', 'url': 'mailto:yaneer@necsi.edu', 'text': 'yaneer@necsi.edu'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': "

Yaneer -

SafeGraph is making its aggregated foot traffic data available for free to help combat the spread of COVID-19. Data includes foot traffic on every commercial place in the U.S. and Canada … and also foot traffic within census block groups.

In this emergency we are giving away the data (at no cost). We are currently working with over 1000 academic groups, government agencies, and task forces including the City of Los Angeles, San Francisco, California Governor's office, Louisville, KY, MIT, Harvard, Brookings, McKinsey, Bain, and many more… we are all collaborating together (we have a shared Slack channel) and working around the clock.

Here is some of the published research we are seeing (just in the past few days) -\xa0"}, {'type': 'link', 'url': 'https://www.safegraph.com/publications'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': '\xa0including the CDC\xa0'}, {'type': 'link', 'url': 'https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/69/wr/mm6915e2.htm?s_cid=mm6915e2_w'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': '

text: here is a nice seroprevalence study. note difference in likely cases vs confirmed is very large. <https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.14.20062463v1>
attachments: [{'service_name': 'medRxiv', 'title': 'COVID-19 Antibody Seroprevalence in Santa Clara County, California', 'title_link': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.14.20062463v1', 'text': "Background Addressing COVID-19 is a pressing health and social concern. To date, many epidemic projections and policies addressing COVID-19 have been designed without seroprevalence data to inform epidemic parameters. We measured the seroprevalence of antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 in Santa Clara County. Methods On 4/3-4/4, 2020, we tested county residents for antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 using a lateral flow immunoassay. Participants were recruited using Facebook ads targeting a representative sample of the county by demographic and geographic characteristics. We report the prevalence of antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 in a sample of 3,330 people, adjusting for zip code, sex, and race/ethnicity. We also adjust for test performance characteristics using 3 different estimates: (i) the test manufacturer's data, (ii) a sample of 37 positive and 30 negative controls tested at Stanford, and (iii) a combination of both. Results The unadjusted prevalence of antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 in Santa Clara County was 1.5% (exact binomial 95CI 1.11-1.97%), and the population-weighted prevalence was 2.81% (95CI 2.24-3.37%). Under the three scenarios for test performance characteristics, the population prevalence of COVID-19 in Santa Clara ranged from 2.49% (95CI 1.80-3.17%) to 4.16% (2.58-5.70%). These prevalence estimates represent a range between 48,000 and 81,000 people infected in Santa Clara County by early April, 50-85-fold more than the number of confirmed cases. Conclusions The population prevalence of SARS-CoV-2 antibodies in Santa Clara County implies that the infection is much more widespread than indicated by the number of confirmed cases. Population prevalence estimates can now be used to calibrate epidemic and mortality projections. ### Competing Interest Statement The authors have declared no competing interest. ### Funding Statement We acknowledge many individual donors who generously supported this project with gift awards. The funders had no role in the design and conduct of the study, nor in the decision to prepare and submit the manuscript for publication. ### Author Declarations All relevant ethical guidelines have been followed; any necessary IRB and/or ethics committee approvals have been obtained and details of the IRB/oversight body are included in the manuscript. Yes All necessary patient/participant consent has been obtained and the appropriate institutional forms have been archived. Yes I understand that all clinical trials and any other prospective interventional studies must be registered with an ICMJE-approved registry, such as <http://ClinicalTrials.gov|ClinicalTrials.gov>. I confirm that any such study reported in the manuscript has been registered and the trial registration ID is provided (note: if posting a prospective study registered retrospectively, please provide a statement in the trial ID field explaining why the study was not registered in advance). Yes I have followed all appropriate research reporting guidelines and uploaded the relevant EQUATOR Network research reporting checklist(s) and other pertinent material as supplementary files, if applicable. Hey <!channel>, <@U0103SMH9G8> just posted this great list of non-pharmaceutical interventions/policy measures databases in a thread over at <#CUXSVD693|analytics-viz-policytracking> (some additions posted in thread below). Pinning it to our channel for easy reference:

World-wide covid interventions: <https://www.acaps.org/covid19-government-measures-dataset>

Governor + state: <https://www.nga.org/coronavirus/#actions> (with links to state pages)
Coded state responses (NGA + KFF): <https://github.com/COVID19StatePolicy/SocialDistancing>
State policy database: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1zu9qEWI8PsOI_i8nI_S29HDGHlIp2lfVMsGxpQ5tvAQ/edit#gid=0>
KFF state data: <https://www.kff.org/health-costs/issue-brief/state-data-and-policy-actions-to-address-coronavirus/>
Legislation: <https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/state-action-on-coronavirus-covid-19.aspx> (with links to state bills)
State Fiscal responses: <https://www.ncsl.org/research/fiscal-policy/state-fiscal-responses-to-covid-19.aspx>
State education responses: <https://www.ncsl.org/research/education/public-education-response-to-coronavirus-covid-19.aspx>
State Election actions: <https://www.ncsl.org/research/elections-and-campaigns/state-action-on-covid-19-and-elections.aspx>
Emergency declarations: <https://astho.org/COVID-19/>
Federal: <https://www.nga.org/coronavirus/>

COVID-19 Correctional Policies & Responses <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1X6uJkXXS-O6eePLxw2e4JeRtM41uPZ2eRcOA_HkPVTk/edit>
Prison visitation & court responses: <https://www.themarshallproject.org/2020/03/17/tracking-prisons-response-to-coronavirus>

Elective medical procedures guidance: <https://disasterresponse.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b4dce71b763a46c7beb0e0b1c8bc27dd>
Testing prioritization guidelines: <https://disasterresponse.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=2f75227356e54a1489ffad7ec293764d>

US County: <https://ce.naco.org/?dset=COVID-19&ind=Emergency%20Declaration%20Types>
US County + city (crowdsourced): <https://github.com/Keystone-Strategy/covid19-intervention-data/>
US County (crowdsourced): <http://hci.st/socialdistancing-dataset>

Metro areas (New Orleans, NYC, San Francisco, Seattle): <https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/69/wr/mm6915e2.htm?s_cid=mm6915e2_e&deliveryName=USCDC_921-DM25761#T1_down>

Red Cross Public Health Emergency Status by county (what is their source?): <https://arc-nhq-gis.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=97792521be744711a291d10ecef33a61>

Economic stimulus by country: <http://web.boun.edu.tr/elgin/COVID.htm>

text:
Hey *<!channel>* to reiterate my post from yesterday we need all hands on deck for the Africa/LatAm crush the curve project!

Is it the most glamorous/exciting work? No, but it is stupidly important. *Completing the sheet I detailed above would give teams all across Slack a valuable resource for identifying key areas for policy action/intervention, outreach, and developing communications materials in countries that may only be at the beginning of their epidemics*. *It would also allow us to evaluate how effective different policies have been.*

Get on the sheet, even if you individually fill in a few rows here and there that gets us closer to finishing. It only took me about an hour to finish Angola.

[{'from_url': 'https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C0108BH13PD/p1586985976044500', 'fallback': '[April 15th, 2020 2:26 PM] zamorajandrew: Thread for request from\xa0<@UURUK8NHJ> to aggregate federal quarantine/shutdown policies across Africa and Latin America. Please use the thread for the team working on this dataset to discuss amongst each other.

Link to portal thread:\xa0<https://necsi-edu.slack.com/archives/C011PFC8J21/p1586900218017200>

Link to Google sheet for the data is below. Please only input values in a cell that match those in parentheses at the head of each column (e.g. only values of National, Affected Areas, or None should be inputted for the "Stay at Home Order" column. Most columns have a rules/additional notes column so you can write out the details (e.g. the rules for who is able to leave home, for how long, etc.). *Please keep additional notes to a 1-2 sentence limit*.

Also note that *this is structured like a time series*. Create new rows for additional dates for whenever a country implemented a policy. For example, for a country that had it's first cases (2 of them) on March 3 and didn't implement any policies until March 11th (526 confirmed cases, shutting down schools and banning gatherings greater than 100 people) would have two rows. One row for March 3, 2020 with "Yes" in the First Cases column, 2 in the Number Confirmed Cases column, and No, None, etc. for every other column and then a second row for March 11, 2020 which would have 526 in the Number Confirmed Cases column and add a "Yes" in the School Closure column and >100 Prohibited in the Large Gatherings Ban column.

Finally, *be sure to hyperlink the article, document, etc. that you got the information from to fill in each cell*

text:
*Welcome to the End Corona-Virus Scanning Team!* (see Daily Update Post by <@UUPTPUHCK> pinned below )

*To get started as a scanner,* 
• Join this channel and introduce yourself!  
• Check out the <https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wrf4zYH7TA4ChhIefyDQ8wIVKAEJxu-o6jIz_XJwQFE/edit|Scanning Welcome Doc> for the bigger picture 
• Check daily pinned updates here to jump right in!!
***Any ECV user, project, channel or team can request scanning on any topic! Use this <https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSf2W-MXKMFHdyGo0VNV8K3wkJgR-5zw2yonPfNzMtTiJVIwvQ/viewform|Form to Request Scanning>.***

Other channels/teams/projects are often too busy to dedicate time solely to information gathering.  Our goal is to deploy swift, efficient teams to fulfil the search for information. When an ECV project or channel needs fast info, they make a request and the scanning team deploys a small “mini-team” to find relevant information.    <@UUPTPUHCK> is available if you have any questions!

text: <https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/116.full|https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/116.full>
attachments: [{'service_name': 'Science', 'title': 'Pandemic brings mass vaccinations to a halt', 'title_link': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/116.full', 'text': "> Science's COVID-19 coverage is supported by the Pulitzer Center. “A devil's choice.” That's how Seth Berkley, head of GAVI, the Vaccine Alliance, describes the dilemma facing global health organizations in the past few weeks. They could either continue to support mass vaccination campaigns in poor countries but risk that they would inadvertently help spread COVID-19—or recommend their suspension, inevitably triggering an upsurge of many other infectious diseases. In the end, they chose the latter, and mass vaccination campaigns against a host of diseases are now grinding to a halt in many countries. For many children, these campaigns are the only chance to get vaccines. Some 13.5 million have already missed out on vaccinations for polio, measles, human papillomavirus, yellow fever, cholera, and meningitis since the suspensions began, Berkley says. “I tell you those numbers will be much larger than what we see today.” The fallout may last long after the pandemic subsides. And in the case of polio, the pause imperils the success of a 3-decade eradication campaign that was already in trouble. The suspensions began on 24 March, when leaders of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative (GPEI) called on countries to postpone all polio vaccination campaigns until the second half of the year. The huge campaigns—door-to-door efforts that reach 400 million to 450 million annually—are the mainstay of the eradication program. Yet, “We had no choice,” says Michel Zaffran of the World Health Organization (WHO), who heads GPEI. The vaccination drives would put both communities and frontline health workers at risk of infection with the coronavirus, he says. But he concedes more children will be paralyzed in countries where polio is still circulating, and the virus will likely spread to countries that are now polio-free. The polio eradication effort is already reeling from setbacks in Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the wild virus is surging, and in Africa, where outbreaks caused by the live polio vaccine itself are spiraling out of control ( Science , 3 January, p. [14][1]). “Everyone was uncomfortable” with suspending campaigns, Zaffran says. But in the end, the only real tension among GPEI leaders was whether to call for a firm halt not only to preventive campaigns, but also to the targeted campaigns in response to the vaccine-derived outbreaks in Africa. Ultimately, “The guidance came from a very high level to pause everything,” says Rebecca Martin of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). (GPEI's Polio Oversight Board is composed of the heads of all the partner agencies, including WHO Director-General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus.) The program will reassess the decision every 2 weeks. On 26 March, WHO's Strategic Advisory Group of Experts on Immunization (SAGE) issued a broader call, recommending that countries stop mass vaccination campaigns against all vaccine-preventable diseases. “Any mass campaigns would go against the idea of social distancing,” says Alejandro Cravioto of the National Autonomous University of Mexico's Faculty of Medicine, who chairs SAGE. Twenty-three countries have already suspended their measles campaigns, and as a result, 78 million children will miss out on the vaccine, says Robb Linkins, a measles expert in CDC's Global Immunization Division. Sixteen other countries are still deciding. Linkins foresees “tragic” consequences. In poor countries, the virus can kill 3% to 6% of those it infects, WHO says, with malnourished children especially at risk. Measles infected an estimated 10 million and killed 140,000 in 2018, the last year for which numbers are complete. And because measles is incredibly contagious, case numbers could quickly surge following the suspensions. Unlike the polio initiative, SAGE stopped short of recommending that countries halt campaigns to quell ongoing outbreaks, but it said they should carefully weigh the risk of an immediate response against that of a delayed one. For now, measles campaigns are continuing in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, where the world's biggest outbreak has so far killed an estimated 6500 children—far more than the recent Ebola outbreak in that country—and sickened more than 340,000. WHO, GAVI, and other health organizations stress that routine immunization of individual children at clinics must continue as much as possible during the pandemic. But health systems in many countries were already stretched thin, and protective gear is often lacking. Berkley fears severe disruptions of routine immunization if health workers are diverted to COVID-19 or become sick or die, or if parents are afraid to bring their children to a clinic. Vaccines may run out as well. Some countries are already experiencing shortages as flights are grounded and borders close, Berkley says. Other essential health services will also be disrupted, says Augustin Augier, executive director of the Alliance for International Medical Action. Every year, ALIMA trains about 500,000 African mothers to diagnose acute, potentially fatal malnutrition in their children; those programs have been suspended. The knock-on consequences of the pandemic “will be much stronger and more lethal for the world's most vulnerable populations,” Augier says. Across all these programs, the goal is to come back hard and fast to regain lost ground once the pandemic is over. In the meantime, WHO says, countries should continue surveillance for vaccine-preventable diseases to figure out where pathogens are circulating and which children are most at risk. But that, too, is a challenge amid the fear and disruption from COVID-19. Berkley sees some hope in the experience in West Africa after the 2014–15 Ebola outbreak. “There was an unprecedented flow of finance and good will,” he says. “We did campaigns once Ebola was over and strengthened routine immunization. We not only recovered coverage levels, but exceeded them.” But that epidemic was largely confined to three countries with a combined population of fewer than 25 million people. This time, the entire world is affected. [1]: <http://www.sciencemag.org/content/367/6473/14>", 'fallback': 'Science: Pandemic brings mass vaccinations to a halt', 'thumb_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/F1.medium.gif', 'ts': 1586502000, 'from_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/116.full', 'thumb_width': 346, 'thumb_height': 440, 'service_icon': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/sites/default/files/images/favicon.ico', 'id': 1, 'original_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/368/6487/116.full'}]

Hey <!channel> we'll be having our first ever general scanning team meeting tomorrow at 2 - 3pm Pacific Standard Time. Stating in PST since that's the time zone that most respondents are in. Zoom call details are in the thread below.

*All are welcomed and encouraged to attend*. We'll be discussing:
1. General format of how the team has been working up till now and thoughts on how to improve
2. Process for uploading information we find to the knowledge base (The Brane) being headed by <@U010ST5TU5N> and his team
3. Proposed scanning team channel structure for streamlining taking in scanning requests and assembling/deploying teams of scanners to work on them
4. Tech proposals for managing team assignment and monitoring scanning project progress
5. Getting to know each other, we've welcomed lots of new members which means we'll be cranking up our project intake next week!
If you didn't respond to my original post with times or are unable to make the call tomorrow, please let me know when you would be available by responding to this thread or DM me. We can set up another zoom call. I want to make sure that everyone gets a chance to give input on how the team works and to get any lingering concerns/questions addressed.

text:
Hi all,

Are US hospitals using a bubble helmet similar to the Italians?
<https://i2-prod.mirror.co.uk/incoming/article21723281.ece/ALTERNATES/s615b/0_Bergamo-3.jpg|https://i2-prod.mirror.co.uk/incoming/article21723281.ece/ALTERNATES/s615b/0_Bergamo-3.jpg>

This is my current understanding: traditional ventilators are a last resort for COVID19 patients, because the mortality rather is high (70-80%).  So doctors are changing to other O2 delivery, like high flow nasal cannula (HFNC).  The disadvantage of HFNC is that by itself it lets exhaled air spread the virus in hospital wards.  So Italians designed a closed loop helmet that delivers high O2 levels and filters exhaled air with HVAC/N95 filter.

Problem is I think Italy have blocked the export of these helmets.  And I'm not sure where FDA stand on bubble helmet regulation.  If you look at the video coverage of Italian hospital these weird helmets are used a lot.  And the Italians are having better success rates in the last two weeks. Maybe part of their success is these helmets.

Does someone have connections to pulmonologists/doctor in the USA to ask about these helmets?

<https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/patient-care-articles/helmet-based-ventilation-is-superior-to-face-mask-for-patients-with-respiratory-distress|https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/patient-care-articles/helmet-based-ventilation-is-superior-to-face-mask-for-patients-with-respiratory-distress>

text:
Request from Chris Bakerlee/Josh Morrison for volunteers to research human challenge trials. Immunology background ideal. Min 10h/wk for 2 weeks, starting this week.

 Hi all, looks like we could use some more “foot soldiers” to assist with research effort over the next 1-2 weeks to help with some focused questions. Anyone know folks who might be interested?
 
 Questions in need of help on:
 1. Who would participate in HCTs and dose-finding studies and normal clinical trials? How would these details intersect with questions about the ethics and utility of HCTs?
 2. For an HCT, what are the technical and ethical considerations that go into developing a challenge virus? How would it be administered?


Here "foot soldiers" = researchers with relevant expertise or who can digest the literature or contact experts to try to answer these questions :wink: Short-term goal is to inform the content of an academic preprint on considerations involving the use of HCTs, and to inform the advocacy Josh is currently doing

These guys are pretty serious, if you understood that and feel called to volunteer lat me know and I'll get you in touch with them

text:
<!channel> Hey team, just want to say that many have been expressing their gratitude for what we've been doing up to this point. Great job and keep it up!

I have my hands full catching up on work-related stuff today, but wanted to point out that we have a few projects either active or looking to get started:
1. Finishing a database on European shutdown/quarantine policies which I am spearheading and can still use help on. The goal here is to target areas that specific countries have not lockdown well enough (e.g. are people still allowed to congregate somewhere?). Outreach teams can then work on this. *DM me for more details.*
2. <@U010PUHQU1W> is heading a scanning team looking through information/evidence pertaining to the efficacy of masks4all. We *need 1-2 volunteers* to join him, please *DM Daniel for more details*.
3. <@UV33BG35F> has put in a request for a scanning team to look into information for how well individuals in different age groups do on ventilators e.g. what their prospects for returning to full health are. *We need 2-3 volunteers. DM me for more details.*
4. <@U010HF48RL6> is curious about technologies that can be used in African nations to coordinate distributed teams since platforms like Slack aren't popular there. *We need 2-3 volunteers. DM me for more details.*
5. *<@U010NKN5VFT> *brought up that it could be really useful to catalogue policies that have been implemented at the municipal/state level to help keep US citizens afloat while they are staying home. *We need at least 3 volunteers* to get this started. *DM me more more details*.
I will dedicate what time I do spend on Slack today to recruitment. You're encouraged to keep an eye on the <#CUVB0V2KV|general-onboarding-intro_yourself> channels to directly reach out to new people that could be useful for your mini-team.

*Big goal for this coming week is to streamline recruitment, scanning request, and knowledge cataloguing processes.*

text:
So I just want to highlight a piece of text from this German top expert group report,
"Making the Fight against the Coronavirus Pandemic Sustainable"

About masks:
"Once the supply of masks to the health care system and nursing and old people's homes has been secured, the wearing of masks should be extended to the entire population. For a tran-sitional period, until sufficient masks from professional production are available, the popula-tion can be provided with information on the independent production of effective masks. At least for all persons who come into contact with persons at risk, it should be introduced as compulsory for such contact (e.g. in care for the elderly). The Asian standard that a mask should be worn in public places for cold symptoms of any kind (i.e. also beyond corona infec-tions) should also be propagated through information campaigns. Acutely, this means that intensive work should be done to eliminate the current supply bottlenecks for masks (and other protective clothing)."
<https://www.ifo.de/DocDL/Coronavirus-Pandemic_Strategy.pdf>

text:
Just got off the phone with my doctor friend who works in Hamilton Ontario. He says that he would like to see a policy change to have more liberal use of non invasive positive pressure ventilation, like c-paps. He said it in theory it will ariolize the virus, and put doctors at risk but there is protective equipment they can use to midigate it. Not sure what to do with this info.

Also the hospital had less people than normal which surprised me.

text:
Hey <!channel> we have *four active scanning projects* to work on:
1. Finishing a database on European shutdown/quarantine policies which I am spearheading and can still use help on. The goal here is to target areas that specific countries have not lockdown well enough (e.g. are people still allowed to congregate somewhere?). Outreach teams can then work on this. *DM me for more details.*
2. Looking up information on covid-19 re-infection i.e. is it possible, what's the evidence, what do we know (if anything) about the dynamics. This will be a key piece of information for another project being developed by <@U010NKN5VFT> and others hoping to leverage potentially immune people to perform high-risk tasks for those who are sick or that have not been infected in their local communities. <@U010K8GMXSS> is heading this effort and we *need 1-2 volunteers* to work with him for a day or two on this and present what they find to Tim. *DM Viljami and he will let you know where he's at*. 
3. <@U010J9XQHST> wants a small scanning team to look up information to build a relational map of covid-19 symptoms, co-morbidities, and other factors influencing infection risk/disease development. We *need 2-3 volunteers* to work on this for a day or two, *DM me to volunteer and I will get you started*. 
4. <@U010PUHQU1W> is heading a scanning team looking through information/evidence pertaining to the efficacy of masks4all. We *need 1-2 volunteers* to join him, please *DM Daniel for more details*. 
The goal of these small scanning teams is so that you have a group of peers to discuss what you find, what the valuable pieces of information are, and what the best way to present it to the appropriate lead, channel, or other endcoronavirus user(s) is. Keep in contact with the individual(s) that put in the original call for input and please use the rest of the scanning channel as a resource if your smaller group is having trouble hashing something out. Keep in contact with me to update the team on how your project is going.

Two questions: *When do you stop shedding?* In a few weeks. *Can you contract it again?* It is unknown, but you might see limited immunity as you do with other coronaviruses.

text: We have a new tool for web scanning. I just got <@UUPTPUHCK> started with it. It is a chrome plugin. It allows you to set up a Google spreadsheet to work with, key column, and a value column, and the navigate the web highlighting key/value pairs, which get posted into the spreadsheet along with the hyperlink to the page where you found it. Google has not yet approved it , and might take a while, so for now, we have to do some hacks to get it to work. Get the zip file,  unzip, <chrome://extensions>, enable developer mode, load unpacked, select the directory where you unzipped it. Agree to let the plugin use your Google Account.  Click past the scary warnings about unverified extension (you will need to click Advanced at the bottom).  To configure the spreadsheet, click on the Coronavirus icon in the toolbar, Options, enter the sheet ID (long sequence of letters and digits in the sheet URL) , key column (e.g. B), value column (e.g. G), Save. Then browse normally, once you found something of interest, highlight the key value (e.g name of a country), Alt-K or Mark Key from the context menu. Then look for the value. Alt-V or Mark Value. Check the spreadsheet, it should be there with hyperlink. If it recognizes it as a date, it will parse it, and it recognizes dates more or less like PHP strtotime.

It allows you to set up a Google spreadsheet to work with, key column, and a value column, and the navigate the web highlighting key/value pairs, which get posted into the spreadsheet along with the hyperlink to the page where you found it. Google has not yet approved it , and might take a while, so for now, we have to do some hacks to get it to work. Get the zip file,  unzip, '}, {'type': 'link', 'url': 'chrome://extensions'}, {'type': 'text', 'text': ', enable developer mode, load unpacked, select the directory where you unzipped it. Agree to let the plugin use your Google Account.  Click past the scary warnings about unverified extension (you will need to click Advanced at the bottom).  To configure the spreadsheet, click on the Coronavirus icon in the toolbar, Options, enter the sheet ID (long sequence of letters and digits in the sheet URL) , key column (e.g. B), value column (e.g. G), Save. Then browse normally, once you found something of interest, highlight the key value (e.g name of a country), Alt-K or Mark Key from the context menu. Then look for the value. Alt-V or Mark Value. Check the spreadsheet, it should be there with hyperlink. If it recognizes it as a date, it will parse it, and it recognizes dates more or less like PHP strtotime.'}]}]}]

~Yes! Thank you. I will go to sleep now, but tomorrow first thing in the morning I will write those guidelines and post them. here. Basically I think it could be something like this:~

~#scanning-contacts (for people who could be useful to work with or influence for leverage)~

~#scanning-narratives-supporting (important comments, arguments, tweets where there is well argued argument which~
~supports our cause)~

~#scanning-narratives-opposing (same but for opposing comments, potentially hazardous strategic disinfo)~

~#scanning-resources (good resources such as lists, websites etc which can be useful)~

~#scanning-organizations (organizations which are aligned and effective)~

~Does that sound sensible? How could I make it better? Should I try to formulate more explicit criteria for being posted in these channels?~

text:
Here is an account from the front lines of Italy which you might find insightful: "I am speaking to all of you from the front line here in Italy, mainly in Florence Tuscany. As you all may know, I am a surgeon and emergency physician and, since 2002, the Clinical Risk Manager for the Florence Healthcare Trust. When the COVID-19 outbreak occurred I felt the necessity to go back to front line and help my collegues, nurses and intensivits, and other specialties to treat the enormous amount of COVD-19 positive symptomatic patients in very severe conditions needing invasive ventilation and/or supported by NIV or CPAP procedures."

text: <https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.24.059576v2|https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.24.059576v2>
attachments: [{'service_name': 'bioRxiv', 'title': 'Introductions and early spread of SARS-CoV-2 in France', 'title_link': 'https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.24.059576v2', 'text': 'Following the emergence of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) in Wuhan, China in December 2019, specific COVID-19 surveillance was launched in France on January 10, 2020. Two weeks later, the first three imported cases of COVID-19 into Europe were diagnosed in France. We sequenced 97 severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) genomes from samples collected between January 24 and March 24, 2020 from infected patients in France. Phylogenetic analysis identified several early independent SARS-CoV-2 introductions without local transmission, highlighting the efficacy of the measures taken to prevent virus spread from symptomatic cases. In parallel, our genomic data reveals the later predominant circulation of a major clade in many French regions, and implies local circulation of the virus in undocumented infections prior to the wave of COVID-19 cases. This study emphasizes the importance of continuous and geographically broad genomic sequencing and calls for further efforts with inclusion of asymptomatic infections. ### Competing Interest Statement The authors have declared no competing interest.', 'fallback': 'bioRxiv: Introductions and early spread of SARS-CoV-2 in France', 'thumb_url': 'https://www.biorxiv.org/sites/default/files/images/biorxiv_logo_homepage7-5-small.png', 'ts': 1588143600, 'from_url': 'https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.24.059576v2', 'thumb_width': 252, 'thumb_height': 252, 'service_icon': 'https://www.biorxiv.org/sites/default/files/images/favicon.ico', 'id': 1, 'original_url': 'https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.24.059576v2'}]

text:
rt PCR currently "gold standard" but also chokepoint in many U.S.  locations.  Swabs, media & reagants also focal supply & distribution issues.    Re lavage - not so much AFIK -  believe cov may initially lodge in upper resp 1st, then seed down bronchial tree, +/- in parallel or before transit via blood circulation.
ddPCR, batch testing, cat scan diagnosis  all up & coming, with CT accepted/established (or near it) overseas.    AI-based CXR diagnosis up & coming further out, see NECSI-affiliated group in Poland on webpage for example.

If anyone has more current/better knowledge please let me know.   Accurate knowledge, recognition of knowledge gaps very important.  Thanks

:flag-az: Азербайджан: особый карантинный режим до 4 мая

text:
Restrictions in Moscow

Telegram Коронавирус. Оперштаб Москвы

Официальный канал оперативного штаба Москвы по ситуации с коронавирусом


:exclamation:️Коронавирус. Дополнительные меры

Мэр Москвы Сергей Собянин принял решения о дополнительных мерах по борьбе с коронавирусом:

:small_blue_diamond:С 22 апреля граждане с подозрением на коронавирус, а также граждане с проявлениями ОРВИ и других острых респираторных заболеваний обязаны соблюдать режим самоизоляции на дому. При этом допускается передвижение в целях получения медпомощи, в том числе с использованием транспортных средств на основании оформленного цифрового пропуска.

:small_blue_diamond:Режим самоизоляции распространяется на всех, кто проживает вместе с гражданами с проявлениями ОРВИ и коронавируса. Допускается передвижение в целях получения медпомощи. Также можно выходить в магазин и аптеку, выбрасывать мусор и гулять с домашними животными в 100 м от дома. 

:small_blue_diamond:В целях контроля за соблюдением режима самоизоляции будут применять технологии электронного мониторинга местоположения, в том числе с использованием технических устройств.

:small_blue_diamond:Цифровой пропуск смогут также получить добровольные помощники, зарегистрированные ГБУ «Моя карьера», а не только в ГБУ «Мосволонтер». 

:small_blue_diamond:Для передвижения по Москве на грузовом транспорте с 22:00 до 06:00 цифровой пропуск не нужен.

Указ Мэра Москвы №47-УМ «О внесении изменений в указы Мэра Москвы от 5 марта 2020 г. No 12-УМ и от 11 апреля 2020 г. No 43-УМ»

<https://www.mos.ru/upload/documents/docs/47-YM(4).pdf|https://www.mos.ru/upload/documents/docs/47-YM(4).pdf>

Now, as some countries see death rates falling, they are looking at how to get back to something resembling normality, and the European Commission has published a roadmap to guide them.2 Reassuringly, the roadmap places epidemiology in the driving seat. The roadmap has three key elements. First, no country should consider lifting restrictions until it is certain that the disease is under control. This will pose a challenge for some, as it presupposes that national authorities have accurate and timely information on cases and deaths. As the United Kingdom’s experience shows, this can be difficult. The importance of this information cannot be overstated. attachments: [{'service_name': 'Bloomberg.com', 'title': 'Harvard Researchers Say Some Social Distancing May Be Needed Into 2022', 'title_link': 'https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-14/harvard-researchers-say-some-distancing-may-be-needed-into-2022?srnd=premium-europe', 'text': 'You read that right. 2022.', 'fallback': 'Bloomberg.com: Harvard Researchers Say Some Social Distancing May Be Needed Into 2022', 'image_url': 'https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iqBZxhSDt5G4/v0/1200x637.png', 'from_url': 'https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-14/harvard-researchers-say-some-distancing-may-be-needed-into-2022?srnd=premium-europe', 'image_width': 471, 'image_height': 250, 'image_bytes': 144428, 'service_icon': 'https://assets.bwbx.io/s3/javelin/public/javelin/images/favicon-black-63fe5249d3.png', 'id': 1, 'original_url': 'https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-14/harvard-researchers-say-some-distancing-may-be-needed-into-2022?srnd=premium-europe'}, {'service_name': 'Science', 'title': 'Projecting the transmission dynamics of SARS-CoV-2 through the postpandemic period', 'title_link': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/04/14/science.abb5793', 'text': 'It is urgent to understand the future of severe acute respiratory syndrome–coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) transmission. We used estimates of seasonality, immunity, and cross-immunity for betacoronaviruses OC43 and HKU1 from time series data from the USA to inform a model of SARS-CoV-2 transmission. We projected that recurrent wintertime outbreaks of SARS-CoV-2 will probably occur after the initial, most severe pandemic wave. Absent other interventions, a key metric for the success of social distancing is whether critical care capacities are exceeded. To avoid this, prolonged or intermittent social distancing may be necessary into 2022. Additional interventions, including expanded critical care capacity and an effective therapeutic, would improve the success of intermittent distancing and hasten the acquisition of herd immunity. Longitudinal serological studies are urgently needed to determine the extent and duration of immunity to SARS-CoV-2. Even in the event of apparent elimination, SARS-CoV-2 surveillance should be maintained since a resurgence in contagion could be possible as late as 2024.', 'fallback': 'Science: Projecting the transmission dynamics of SARS-CoV-2 through the postpandemic period', 'image_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/04/14/science.abb5793/F1.large.jpg', 'ts': 1586847600, 'from_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/04/14/science.abb5793', 'image_width': 541, 'image_height': 250, 'image_bytes': 122454, 'service_icon': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/sites/default/files/images/favicon.ico', 'id': 2, 'original_url': 'https://science.sciencemag.org/content/early/2020/04/14/science.abb5793'}]

attachments: [{'service_name': 'medRxiv', 'title': 'COVID-19 pandemics modeling with SEIR(+CAQH), social distancing, and age stratification. The effect of vertical confinement and release in Brazil.', 'title_link': 'https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.09.20060053v2', 'text': 'The ongoing COVID-19 epidemics poses a particular challenge to low and middle income countries, making some of them consider the strategy of vertical confinement. In this strategy, contact is reduced only to specific groups (like age groups) that are at increased risk of severe disease following SARS-CoV-2 infection. We aim to assess the feasibility of this scenario as an exit strategy for the current lockdown in terms of its ability to keep the number of cases under the health care system capacity. We developed a modified SEIR model, including confinement, asymptomatic transmission, quarantine and hospitalization. The population is subdivided into 9 age groups, resulting in a system of 72 coupled nonlinear differential equations. The rate of transmission is dynamic and derived from the observed delayed fatality rate; the parameters of the epidemics are derived with a Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithm. We used Brazil as an example of middle income country, but the results are easily generalizable to other countries considering a similar strategy. We find that starting from 60% horizontal confinement, an exit strategy on May 1st of confinement of individuals older than 60 years old and full release of the younger population results in 400 000 hospitalizations, 50 000 ICU cases, and 120 000 deaths in the 50-60 years old age group alone. The health care system avoids collapse if the 50-60 years old are also confined, but our model assumes an idealized lockdown where the confined are perfectly insulated from contamination, so our numbers are a conservative lower bound. Our results discourage confinement by age as an exit strategy. ### Competing Interest Statement The authors have declared no competing interest. ### Funding Statement No external funding was received ### Author Declarations All relevant ethical guidelines have been followed; any necessary IRB and/or ethics committee approvals have been obtained and details of the IRB/oversight body are included in the manuscript.
